qas.question: Who was the founder of the Kirata dynasty?
What geographical part of Kathmandu did Yambu once occupy?
Speakers of what languages sometimes call Kathmandu Yambu?
Where in Kathmandu was Yengal located?
What religion did the Sankhu monastery belong to?

context: Very few historical records exist of the period before the medieval Licchavis rulers. According to Gopalraj Vansawali, a genealogy of Nepali monarchs, the rulers of Kathmandu Valley before the Licchavis were Gopalas, Mahispalas, Aabhirs, Kirants, and Somavanshi. The Kirata dynasty was established by <a0_0>Yalamber<a0_0/>. During the Kirata era, a settlement called Yambu existed in the <a1_0>northern<a1_0/> half of old Kathmandu. In some of the <a2_0>Sino-Tibetan<a2_0/> languages, Kathmandu is still called Yambu. Another smaller settlement called Yengal was present in the <a3_0>southern half<a3_0/> of old Kathmandu, near Manjupattan. During the reign of the seventh Kirata ruler, Jitedasti, <a4_0>Buddhist<a4_0/> monks entered Kathmandu valley and established a forest monastery at Sankhu.
